ENG-186,"Pesin, David (dapesin42)","Pesin, David (dapesin42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Engineering,Computer Science,"Hilal, Amr","Object detection models based on convolutional architectures perform well on standard validation datasets, yet remain prone to hard false positives. These misclassifications often occur due to feature sharing between classes, causing hard false positives during inference. Presently, literature primarily represents misclassifications in confusion matrices or through other performance metrics, but the specific attributes in the feature space are unclear. In this work, we will investigate the geometry of misclassifications in Faster R-CNN and You Only Look Once (YOLO) models by extracting per-object region-of-interest (RoI) feature embeddings from a model pretrained on COCO and applying unsupervised clustering techniques to analyze where misclassified examples exist in feature-space relative to correct classifications and visualize confusion boundaries.",Research Project,Feature-Space Analysis of Misclassifications in Object Detection Through Clustering,Yes,No,No,Computer Science,ENG - Computer Science,,,,,,,ENG,College of Engineering,,,2026,82
ENG-187,"Chastain, Isaiah (ipchastain42)","Chastain, Isaiah (ipchastain42);Gannod, Trejan (tgannod42);Starkey, Lucas (lstarkey42);Lampkins, Trigg (ttlampkins42);Gonzalez, Mikel (magonzalez44)",Undergraduate Student,College of Engineering,Computer Science,"Eberle, William","Universities make big operational decisions—cleaning schedules, event locations, promotional placement—without actually knowing how people move through campus spaces. That’s a problem. This project explores whether anonymized Wi‑Fi access point (WAP) data can be used to realistically model pedestrian movement at TTU. We will start with the engineering quad and analyze timestamped device connections to uncover when and where traffic patterns emerge. Each anonymized device becomes a movement timeline—a sequence of WAP connections over time. We model the buildin